<subSubSection id="4D52440CA9B06C39542F7B7A2A5175DC" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" type="herb, rhizomatous">
<paragraph id="A70D035576E4649182FB042F49630C18" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">
<pageBreakToken id="0F72BB00B0123DB234937BD27E0729F5" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" start="start">Herb</pageBreakToken>
, rhizomatous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0F7E026189A83F47B4E3427CD4A8D832" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">
Rhizome, densely white villous, 2-3 cm long, 0.7-1 cm in diam. Stipule green, 1.5-2 
<normalizedToken id="BE76ED395E63F8C761B9FD601DFECAE7" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-1.5 cm, widely ovate, apex acute to obtuse, margin ciliate. Leaves: petiole erect, densely white villous, 6-13 cm long, 1-3 mm in diam.; blade green, asymmetric, widely ovate, 8.5-18 
<normalizedToken id="111F7255E7C482072CC99FEB2B00C2B0" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
7-12 cm, rugose, usually with one obtuse lobe; base cordate, apex acuminate or acute, margin slightly denticulate, ciliate; adaxially green, densely tubercular-based setose, abaxially pale green, reddish when young, densely villous on veins; venation palmate, 5-6 primary veins, 2 or 3 secondary veins brunching dichotomous, tertiary veins reticulate. Inflorescence: dichasial cyme, peduncle 12-15 cm long, villous; bracts not seen. Staminate flower: pedicels 0.5-1 cm long; tepals 4; outer tepals 2, broadly ovate, 7-11 
<normalizedToken id="2D495CBB5E336229DB482FA4642383A7" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-8 mm, apex rounded to acute, margin entire sometimes serrate and ciliate; inner tepals 2, oblanceolate, 5-7 
<normalizedToken id="699535917B063921DC3EFFA507CDA330" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.8-2 mm, apex obtuse to acute, margin entire; androecium actinomorphic, stamens numerous; filaments longer than anthers, slightly fused at base; anthers yellow, 1-1.2 mm long, shorter than filaments, with two longitudinal slits. Pistillate flower: pedicel 1.2-2 cm long; tepals 2, white or pinkish, widely obovate to orbicular, 0.5-1 
<normalizedToken id="667DB7DFDA05E1E4F8235BD093EFC781" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-1 cm, apex acute, margin entire; styles 2-3, free; stigmas bilobed with twisted bands; ovary green or pinkish, trigonous ellipsoid, 1-1.5 cm long, 0.5-1 cm in diam. (wings excluded), white or red villous, 1-loculed; placentation parietal, placentae 3, 2-branched. Capsule pale green to pink, trigonous-ellipsoid, 1-1.5 cm long, 0.5-1 cm in diam. (wings excluded), villous, brownish when dried, 3-winged unequally; abaxial wing lunate, 0.9-1.2 
<normalizedToken id="059150BA6553D684A3E42DE28FDA2BB0" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.7 mm; lateral wings lunate, 0.9-1.2
<normalizedToken id="99D4807F7014243DC4F2DB2E60ACC51E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2-0.5 cm. Seeds oblong, ca. 0.2 mm long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BBCCBD717E8F2A26534CE19368D2E077" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="D9A0BCEFA08731DBFB041F4DFFDDE542" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FD8E693276F11729C6D2A8DF1AC2E7A3" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Flowering in March-May, fruiting in April-June.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5378326F7017E4764922B0BD813BAF31" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="43C3507EA7224E1FC955619BAA99DDFC" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F60DD36D0756222407C8B211D2EE3773" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">The epithet refers to the dense villous trichomes of the new species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C5BE2568A34383B7320BF817FD6AC679" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="1936E5BF6CF6E894911B96BA9F141C24" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B08574125A6DEF3423C743B32F33D5D7" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">The species only grows on cliffs in limestone forests.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6CE199F267CC2E34C770ADD6651FF6C1" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C6418082D7130E93C9D3C0727D4765ED" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A0E886DB83629B99BEA45B1C79990F68" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">The species occurs exclusively in Ba Be National Park (Cho Ra county) of Bac Kan Province in Vietnam.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8B09D401C03F47E3C071883F3ACBC27" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" type="notes">
<paragraph id="E468806FA1B6B53DB142AA40C14DB1BB" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C79E8F998F183D13E33162C25E529003" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">
In 
<taxonomicName id="2598FEC0AB0E3296BA5CC1CCC8D4B04D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia subsp. sect." order="Cucurbitales" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Coelocentrum" species="guangxiensis" subSpecies="sect.">Begonia sect. Coelocentrum</taxonomicName>
, the new species is similar as 
<taxonomicName id="E464C47D27213579F3EB900E28B776EA" authorityName="C. Y. Wu" authorityYear="1997" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia guangxiensis" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="guangxiensis">
<emphasis id="601DE1E9F985A4CEA3C29F9EECCEB1D1" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Begonia guangxiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the dense hairy habit, mainly differing in the dense tubercular-based pubes on the abaxial surface of leaves (
<emphasis id="6B0EEA59946F1DCDC241AAF681F98C5C" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">vs.</emphasis>
villous trichomes in the latter species) and subequal wings (
<emphasis id="726F96529E22D4C4D0B600F9959160D7" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">vs.</emphasis>
unequal) (
<bibRefCitation id="8F0297A80B3FEE01F38A9598F290290C" author="Wu, CY" journalOrPublisher="Acta Phytotaxonomica Sinica" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" pagination="43 - 56" refId="B27" refString="Wu, CY, Ku, TC, 1997. New taxa of the Begonia L. (Begoniaceae) from China (Cont.). Acta Phytotaxonomica Sinica 35 (1): 43 - 56" title="New taxa of the Begonia L. (Begoniaceae) from China (Cont.)." volume="35" year="1997">Wu and Ku 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="ABD293B9060D56ED4BC1C55CCD5F2886" author="Shui, Y-M" journalOrPublisher="Yunnan Science and Technology Press, Kunming" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" refId="B21" refString="Shui, Y-M, Chen, W-H, 2017. Begonia of China. Yunnan Science and Technology Press, Kunming" title="Begonia of China." year="2017">Shui and Chen 2017</bibRefCitation>
). It is also similar as 
<taxonomicName id="124764E558620B2D794435D1311F5720" genus="B." lsidName="B. calciphila" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="calciphila">
<emphasis id="87B33EA7ECCE8485674BE979CE8D1C77" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">B. calciphila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
C.-I Peng in the shape and trichomes of leaves, but differs in 0.5-1.2 cm long stout inter-nodes (
<emphasis id="43F70602C345976841603AAF88E92688" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">vs.</emphasis>
1.5-4.5 cm long slender inter-nodes) and hairy flowers and fruits (
<emphasis id="DBFE7DA48DD298500C430A9ADD6A53FC" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">vs.</emphasis>
glabrous in the latter species) (
<bibRefCitation id="BC8BAB1D2F76BDB1570BC4798D226E76" author="Peng, CI" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="13" pageNumber="78" pagination="083 - 099" refId="B19" refString="Peng, CI, Yang, HA, Kono, Y, Jung, MJ, Nguyen, TH, 2015b. Four new species of Begonia (Begoniaceae) from Vietnam: B. abbreviata, B. calciphila, B. sphenantheroides and B. tamdaoensis. Phytotaxa 222 (2): 083 - 099" title="Four new species of Begonia (Begoniaceae) from Vietnam: B. abbreviata, B. calciphila, B. sphenantheroides and B. tamdaoensis." volume="222" year="2015 b">Peng et al. 2015b</bibRefCitation>
). In Bac Kan Province, Vietnam, there are four new species already described, viz. 
<taxonomicName id="815AC94375571D81A0297FB576FA3F8A" genus="B." lsidName="B. regosula" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="regosula">
<emphasis id="C4911E7B9E5EB2664B4BDB324B3FE542" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">B. regosula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Aver., 
<taxonomicName id="DCE520F113ACAC8B2986DFE2669A9ACA" genus="B." lsidName="B. babeana" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" rank="species" species="babeana">
<emphasis id="972C1C9419FAE7294F48CD15FA22A485" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">B. babeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Aver. &amp; H.Q. Nguyen (
<bibRefCitation id="967544EE3896F909FF103BA3167B660F" author="Averyanov, LV" journalOrPublisher="Turczaninowia" pageId="12" pageNumber="77" pagination="5 - 32" refId="B2" refString="Averyanov, LV, Nguyen, HQ, 2012. Eleven new species of Begonia L. (Begoniaceae) from Laos and Vietnam. Turczaninowia 15 (2): 5 - 32" title="Eleven new species of Begonia L. (Begoniaceae) from Laos and Vietnam." volume="15" year="2012">Averyanov and Nguyen 2012</bibRefCitation>
) and two more new species described in this paper.
</paragraph>
